# This file is used by "git commit" to auto-populate the commit message template:
#   git config commit.template .gitmessage
#   git commit --template=.gitmessage


# === Header (required) ===
# Conventional Commits format:
#   type[optional scope][optional !]: description
#
# Keep the header at 50 characters or fewer.
# Use a lowercase imperative description.
# Do not end the header with a period.
# Separate the header from the body with a blank line.
# Examples:
#   docs: align commit rules
#   fix(path): preserve cleanup
#   feat(tools): add ruff installer
#   feat(tools)!: remove legacy shim

# <type>[optional scope][optional !]: <description>


# === Body (optional but recommended) ===
# Describe the context, rationale, and solution.
# Explain *what* and *why* (not *how*). Include related issue or
# task ID when available.
# Focus on the "why", not just the "what". Max 72 characters per line.
# Wrap at 72 chars. ################################## which is here:  #
#
# Example:
#   The previous loader crashed when the config file was empty.
#   Added guard clauses and default values to ensure stability.

# <body>


# === Footers (optional) ===
# Use trailer-like metadata for references, reviews, acknowledgements,
# and breaking changes.
# Max 72 characters per line.
# Wrap at 72 chars. ################################## which is here:  #
#
# Examples:
#   Refs: PROJ-1289
#   Fixes: #42
#   BREAKING CHANGE: remove support for legacy shims

# <footers>
